Live for 30 days in the field as a volunteer, alongside people who work closely with nature or rural systems—like farmers, forest workers, or others in your chosen theme—no laptops—just your senses and a notebook.
Goal: Live like a local. Work in the field. Understand the system.
Evaluation: Immersion quality, observation depth, engagement with locals, and field journal reflections

div.font: After living in the field, you take time to pause and think. You revisit what you saw, felt, and heard—looking for patterns, pain points, and open questions. With mentor support, you turn those raw experiences into one clear problem that you deeply understand and are ready to work on.
Goal: Find the one problem that truly matters—with mentor support and a clear process.
Evaluation: Depth of insight, clarity of problem framing, use of field experience, and reflection quality

div.font: Use what you experienced in Round 1 to pick one real problem that stood out to you. You’ll be placed into a team by the organizers to explore the problem, come up with ideas, and build a basic solution—just like in an ideathon. The round ends with a pitch to mentors.
Goal: Problem Ownership + First Steps of Solution
Evaluation: Relevance of problem selected, teamwork, quality of ideas, clarity of pitch, and solution potential

div.font:
Start with an intensive week-long hackathon to focus on your selected problem. Work with your team to deeply understand the problem, frame it clearly, and explore possible solutions. This phase is about translating your insight into an actionable idea.
Goal: Understand your problem deeply and frame a practical solution idea.
Mode: Sprint + Collaboration
Evaluation: Clarity of problem statement, originality of idea, team collaboration, and solution potential

Mode: Field Testing + Mentorship
Evaluation: Technical feasibility, clarity of prototype logic, response to early field feedback, and consistency in weekly progress

Mode: Piloting + Expert Feedback
Evaluation: Usability, performance improvements, responsiveness to user feedback, and effectiveness of field testing

Mode: Final Validation + Peer & Mentor Review
Evaluation: Solution completeness, readiness for deployment, quality of documentation, and peer/mentor validation

Mode: Field Deployment + Partner Collaboration
Evaluation: Real-world usability, user adoption, quality of improvements, completeness of documentation, and readiness for transfer or scale
